rian identities? Although the empire has been commonly viewed as a Hindu bulwark against Islamic incursion from the north or as a religiously ecumenical state, Valerie Stoker argues that the Vijayanagara court was selective in its patronage of religious institutions. To understand the dynamic interaction between religious and royal institutions in this period, she focuses on the career of the Hindu intellectual and monastic leader Vyasatirtha. An agent of the state and a powerful religious authority, Vyasatirtha played an important role in expanding the empire's economic and social networks. By examining his polemics against rival sects in the context of his work for the empire, Stoker provides a remarkably nuanced picture of the relationship between religious identity and sociopolitical reality under Vijayanagara rule.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHinduism and statezIndiazVijayanagar (Empire)xHistoryy16th century. 0aVyāsatīrtha,d1460-1539xInfluence. 7aHISTORY / Asia / India & South Asia.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066754740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520965461?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520965461zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520965461/original  a978-3-11-064982-6 Asian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Package  a978-3-11-066754-7 University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA